<subSubSection lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="426" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1994,2019]" lastBlockId="1.[151,1436,151,501]" lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="426" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,267,1994,2019]" pageId="0" pageNumber="425">Remarks.</emphasis>
The following genus-level characters supplement the original description by 
<bibRefCitation author="Viraktamath, C. A. &amp; Anantha Murthy, H. V." lastPageId="1" lastPageNumber="426" pageId="0" pageNumber="425" pagination="39 - 55" refId="ref1494" refString="Viraktamath, C. A. &amp; Anantha Murthy, H. V. (1999) A revision of the leafhopper tribe Scaphytopiini from India and Nepal. Senckenbergiana Biologica, 79 (1), 39 - 55." type="journal article" year="1999">Viraktamath &amp; Murthy (1999)</bibRefCitation>
. Prothoracic femur row AV with several short, stout setae, IC with 9 long setae (
<figureCitation box="[1174,1260,151,176]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–26" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1272,1294]" captionTargetBox="[220,1418,273,1197]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[150,1436,193,1251]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 21–26. Univagris pallida Virakthamath &amp; Murthy. 21. Prothoracic femur, 22. Mesothoracic leg, 23. Mesothoracic tarsus, 24. Metathoracic leg, 25. Metathoracic femur, 26. Metathoracic tarsus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="426">Fig. 21</figureCitation>
). Mesothoracic femur with AV setae short (
<figureCitation box="[459,542,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–26" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1272,1294]" captionTargetBox="[220,1418,273,1197]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[150,1436,193,1251]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 21–26. Univagris pallida Virakthamath &amp; Murthy. 21. Prothoracic femur, 22. Mesothoracic leg, 23. Mesothoracic tarsus, 24. Metathoracic leg, 25. Metathoracic femur, 26. Metathoracic tarsus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="426">Fig. 22</figureCitation>
), Segment I of fore and mid tarsi with numerous macrosetae ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[1340,1422,188,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[175,1431,226,1778]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,193,2007]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Univagris tenebra sp. nov. 1. Dorsal habitus, 2. Lateral habitus, 3. Pronotum, 4. Face, 5. Pygofer, 6–8. Aedeagus dorsal, lateral, ventral, 9. Style, 10. Subgenital plate, valve and style." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608151/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="426">Fig.2 3</figureCitation>
). Metathoracic femur with setal formula 2+1+1 (
<figureCitation box="[677,813,223,248]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–26" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1272,1294]" captionTargetBox="[220,1418,273,1197]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[150,1436,193,1251]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 21–26. Univagris pallida Virakthamath &amp; Murthy. 21. Prothoracic femur, 22. Mesothoracic leg, 23. Mesothoracic tarsus, 24. Metathoracic leg, 25. Metathoracic femur, 26. Metathoracic tarsus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="426">Figs. 24, 25</figureCitation>
). Metathoracic tibia flattened, row PD with macrosetae, AD spinelike, AV with macrosetae, PV with numerous long setae, tarsomere II less than 1/2 length of tarsomere I, tarsomere I with 3–4 platellae (
<figureCitation box="[501,585,295,320]" captionStart="FIGURES 21–26" captionStartId="4.[151,264,1272,1294]" captionTargetBox="[220,1418,273,1197]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[150,1436,193,1251]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURES 21–26. Univagris pallida Virakthamath &amp; Murthy. 21. Prothoracic femur, 22. Mesothoracic leg, 23. Mesothoracic tarsus, 24. Metathoracic leg, 25. Metathoracic femur, 26. Metathoracic tarsus." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2608153/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="426">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,151,501]" pageId="1" pageNumber="426">
The genus differs from related genera in having a single median process of the connective with which the aedeagus is fused, and a broadened style apex. It shares the fused aedeagus and connective with 
<emphasis box="[1329,1436,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="426">Thyaksha</emphasis>
Viraktamath &amp; Murthy and 
<taxonomicName authority="Viraktamath &amp; Webb. The" authorityName="Viraktamath &amp; Webb. The" authorityYear="2006" box="[468,894,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Sikhamani" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="426" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[468,586,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="426">Sikhamani</emphasis>
Viraktamath &amp; Webb. The
</taxonomicName>
latter differ in having the male pygofer without any process and the style apex broadened
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
